## 3. Design Doctrine

### 3.1 Mirror Before Hammer

The system first reflects the common human meaning of the word.

This prevents clever decomposition from becoming detached from lived experience.

```text
Resonate first.
Differentiate second.
Guide third.
```

### 3.2 Walking Spider Progression

The player moves one conceptual foothold at a time.

Each distinction should create the next available distinction.

The system should avoid dumping a complete taxonomy before the player has felt the structure.

```text
Sense â Anchor â Step â Propagate â Step Again
```

### 3.3 Hammer

The Hammer breaks an overloaded word into distinctions that matter.

Valid fractures may be based on:

- cause
- mechanism
- timing
- scale
- perspective
- intention
- context
- outcome
- controllability
- emotional texture
- social function
- developmental history

### 3.4 Kintsugi

Kintsugi does not erase the fractures.

It makes the relationships among fragments part of the artifact.

A repaired word should show:

- where categories overlap
- where they differ
- which categories transform into others
- which categories are causes, outcomes, or interpretations
- where uncertainty remains

### 3.5 ZPC

ZPC compresses the repaired structure into the smallest representation that can still be reliably reconstructed.

A good ZPC object should be:

- compact
- memorable
- expandable
- teachable
- machine-readable
- useful outside the game

