## 8. Game Modes

### 8.1 Classic Belt

One word at a time. Increasing speed.

### 8.2 Walking Spider

No timer. Each valid distinction unlocks the next prompt.

Best for learning.

### 8.3 Lightning Hammer

Short timer. Player must produce a minimum viable reconstruction.

Best for fluency.

### 8.4 Kintsugi Mode

Fragments are supplied. Player must repair their relationships.

Best for systems thinking.

### 8.5 ZPC Mode

A full taxonomy is supplied. Player must compress it without losing reconstructability.

Best for memory and interface design.

### 8.6 Mirror Duel

Two players reconstruct the same word.

Judging compares where their category systems converge and diverge.

### 8.7 Hydra Mode

Each accepted category becomes a new mole word.

Example:

```text
Luck
 ââ Prepared Luck
 ââ Timing Luck
 ââ Social Luck
```

The category tree recursively generates future rounds.

### 8.8 Community Forge

Players collaboratively improve an existing reconstruction.

The score rewards synthesis rather than individual ownership alone.

### 8.9 Adversarial Mole

The system presents deceptive near-synonyms, politically loaded terms, euphemisms, or words with hidden frame assumptions.

Best for epistemic resilience.

